gets shut out.

00:12:18.196 --> 00:12:20.198 position:50% align:center
Till eventually, you're breaking
your back for someone

00:12:20.281 --> 00:12:22.409 position:50% align:center
higher up the food chain
than you can even see

00:12:22.492 --> 00:12:24.494 position:50% align:center
in hopes that it's
what they want.

00:12:24.577 --> 00:12:26.830 position:50% align:center
[GIRL F] So that means
you're servile, doesn't it?

00:12:26.913 --> 00:12:28.289 position:50% align:center
Sure does.

00:12:28.373 --> 00:12:31.209 position:50% align:center
It can be weird listening
to grown-ups talk as a kid.

00:12:31.292 --> 00:12:33.253 position:50% align:center
When you hear adults
having a conversation,

00:12:33.336 --> 00:12:36.923 position:50% align:center
it always sounds too complicated
to ever understand, right?

00:12:37.007 --> 00:12:37.924 position:50% align:center
Yeah, true.

00:12:38.008 --> 00:12:39.634 position:50% align:center
All smoke and mirrors.

00:12:39.718 --> 00:12:40.760 position:50% align:center
'Cause most of the things

00:12:40.844 --> 00:12:42.762 position:50% align:center
they're talking about
are dead simple.

00:12:42.846 --> 00:12:44.806 position:50% align:center
But the goal isn't
to be understood.

00:12:44.889 --> 00:12:46.808 position:50% align:center
They wanna distract each
other from the truth,

00:12:46.891 --> 00:12:47.892 position:50% align:center
not discuss it.

00:12:47.976 --> 00:12:49.436 position:50% align:center
So instead of getting
to the point,

00:12:49.519 --> 00:12:52.313 position:50% align:center
they hide it under a
pile of grown-up words.

00:12:52.397 --> 00:12:53.898 position:50% align:center
And the bigger they
make that pile,

00:12:53.982 --> 00:12:57.235 position:50% align:center
the less likely anyone will
be willing to dig through it.

00:12:57.318 --> 00:12:59.487 position:50% align:center
You know when your parents are
scolding you for something

00:12:59.571 --> 00:13:02.532 position:50% align:center
and you try to get 'em off your
back by changing the subject?

00:13:02.615 --> 00:13:05.535 position:50% align:center
It's basically the grown-up
version of that.

00:13:05.618 --> 00:13:08.079 position:50% align:center
As you get older, you kids
are gonna be picking up

00:13:08.163 --> 00:13:10.206 position:50% align:center
lots of difficult new words.

00:13:10.290 --> 00:13:11.374 position:50% align:center
Words people made up

00:13:11.458 --> 00:13:13.877 position:50% align:center
to keep their old excuses
sounding fresh.

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:17.255 position:50% align:center
Or at least,
that's what I think.

00:13:17.339 --> 00:13:19.758 position:50% align:center
[USAHARA]
So is he gonna cue us or...?

00:13:19.841 --> 00:13:21.634 position:50% align:center
[KUMATANI]
Yesterday,

00:13:21.718 --> 00:13:24.471 position:50% align:center
Uramichi took me out to
this <i>yakiniku</i> joint.

00:13:24.554 --> 00:13:27.307 position:50% align:center
[USAHARA] Uh! What the hell?
I wanted to go!

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:30.143 position:50% align:center
[KUMATANI] And he said
something genuinely kind.

00:13:30.226 --> 00:13:32.270 position:50% align:center
No venom at all.

00:13:32.354 --> 00:13:34.481 position:50% align:center
It could have been a line
out of a kids' movie.

00:13:34.564 --> 00:13:36.608 position:50% align:center
It was so un-Uramichi.

00:13:36.691 --> 00:13:38.943 position:50% align:center
Not gonna lie,
I was kinda creeped out,

00:13:39.027 --> 00:13:43.656 position:50% align:center
but I'm pretty sure he meant it
from the bottom of his heart.

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:45.575 position:50% align:center
I don't know if he can
even believe kind words

00:13:45.658 --> 00:13:46.910 position:50% align:center
